    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-03-07T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-03-07T07:00:00-05:00" n="168"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d168">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">84D.24/32: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Ireland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gray</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dublin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-03-07T13:00:00+01:00"
                            >March 7, 1941—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 3:23 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>26. Your 11, February 28, 6 p.m. Aiken on his way to Washington. On March 3 I
                    called on Prime Minister and transmitted your views as to existing priority
                    situation for obtaining American arms and munitions and your suggestion that the
                    envoy be instructed to cooperate with British Purchasing Commission to ensure
                    quick deliveries. I subscribe wholeheartedly to the implications of this
                    suggestion. <pb facs="0230" n="222" xml:id="pg_222"/> Last summer I endeavored
                    to enlist your good offices to procure arms for Irish Government direct from
                        America.<note n="14" xml:id="d168fn14">See <ref target="frus1940v03#pg_160">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1940, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, pp. 160</ref> ff.</note> I wish formally
                    to recede from this position in view of changed conditions and fuller knowledge.
                    This is not to be taken as an alarmist warning but as common prudence in view of
                    unfortunate possibilities. If, as I suspect, you believe the decision to arm
                    Ireland to be primarily a British responsibility I agree entirely …</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gray</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
